metadata.name: BLACK MATTER-NGC 1569
metadata.description:
This fantastic black matter was born in galaxies 
NGC 1569 is a dwarf irregular galaxy in Camelopardalis.  
NGC 1569 is smaller than the Small Magellanic Cloud, 
but brighter than the latter or the Large Magellanic 
Cloud.  
NASA's Hubble Space Telescope has imaged one of the most 
active galaxies in our local neighborhood. NGC 1569, 
sparkles with the light from millions of newly formed 
young stars. At the nucleus of the starburst galaxy is 
a grouping of three giant star clusters, each containing 
more than a million stars. The clusters reside in a 
large, central cavity. The gas in the cavity has been 
blown out by the multitude of massive, young stars that 
already exploded as supernovae. NGC 1569 is located 11 
million light-years from Earth in the constellation 
Camelopardalis.
